Introduction

With the implementation of the first parachain auctions, the Kusama network reached a major milestone and it is exciting to see that many parachain projects are ready to participate. In this post, we reiterate the happenings with the first five auctions, take a closer look on the contribution dynamics of the crowdloans and take an outlook on potential future developments. We will crunch some numbers, but nothing too complicated. The data is based on the crowdloan.contribute events as well as the results from an anonymous survey conducted with \(n=15\) parachain teams prior to the auctions (at the end of March / early April). Before the auction, it was clear that there will be popular demand for the Kusama slots where 80% of teams indicated that they are aiming for both a Kusama and Polkadot slot (with 13.3% only Kusama and 6.7% only Polkadot) with 10 of 15 teams indicating that they want to bid for the first available slots. On a scale from 1-7, with an average of 6.5, teams indicated that they extensively thought about the parachain auctions and how to acquire a slot.

To start off, let us look get an overview about some metrics with regard to the crowdloans at the end of all auctions.

The Candle Auction: A refresher

Before continuing with the analysis of the individual auctions, it is a good idea to reiterate on the the auction mechanism. The candle auction is an old auction format from the around the 16th century where bidding was allowed until a literal candle went out. This was used to induce uncertainty about the actual ending time of the action, because sniping already was a known issue. This phenomenon describes the situation that bidders hold back their bids until the last possible moment to squeeze their bid in and not give other participants the chance to react. Whoever participated in some online auctions like eBay knows the situation. As we want to avoid sniping in our auctions (with some other undesired things, see LINK), the candle auction is also used to auction off the parachain slots for Polkadot and Kusama. In contrast to the ancient candle auction, the end is determined retrospectively. That means, the auction always has a fixed length and only after it ended, a verified random function (VRF-LINK) determines the block that marks the end of the auction. We can use four checkpoints to describe the temporal procedure of a candle auction, described in block height. The following graph illustrates the process.

Start |—–(Starting Period)————| Start candle phase | –(Candle Phase)—–| termination block | —(Candle Phase)——–| End <- having a nice graphic here. The dots could be blocks and there are 4 specially colored blocks. The phases are span above it.

The first two checkpoints, start and end block are rather obvious. Next, and exactly 27,000 blocks (around 45 hours) after the starting block of the auction, the candle phase (or ending phase) starts. Until the start of the ending phase, the candle mechanism is deactivated and each block there has a zero probability to end the auction. This was implemented to give both the teams and contributors time to familiarize themselves with the auction and to set up their strategies. The candle phase (or ending phase) marks the beginning of where, figuratively, the candle is lit and lasts for 72’000 blocks (around 5 days). During the candle phase, the auction can end at any given block with equal probability (i.e., the candle phase has a uniform termination profile) (footnote: To reduce storage requirements, only every 20th block can be the termination block). Bidding is allowed until the end of the auction. After the end a VRF randomly chooses the actual ending block (“termination block”) and implements the state of the auction at that block. Later bids are discarded and, in the case of crowdloans, contributions remain locked for the whole duration of the slot, but did not actually contribute to a higher bid. Therefore, the candle mechanism induces incentives to bid as early as possible (or at least shortly before the beginning of the candle phase) and thereby reduce sniping. For more information see WIKI and BLOGPOST.

Crowdloan Mechanism

Crowdloans are modules in the runtime of Kusama and Polkadot (EXPLAIN) to source funds from the community in a trustless way. The funds are locked on the relay chain (LINK) but will be paid back to the users. A user thereby pays only the opportunity costs of their locked token (mostly the forgone staking rewards) but can be sure to receive the funds back at the end of the slot. The strategy is fixed. A crowdloan is therefore a vessel where bids of many individual users are funneled and it automatically increases the bidA crowdloan bids in the auction automatically whenever a new contribution comes in (during the ending phase. In the beginning phase, it waits and only posts a bid once the beginning phase starts. This has been done to reduce storage needs). Therefore, in the absence of individual bidders, tracking the crowdloan contributions over time is equal to tracking the bids in the auction.

Auction Data

In total, the first sequence of auctions sold five slots on the Kusama network. The first auction started at the 15th of June and the last auction ended on the 20th of July. Each auction lasted seven days with a two day starting period and five days of candle period. All contestants for the slots participated via crowdloans (there were a few non-serious bids for some smaller packages that was probably due to visibility or fund). In the survey, 86.7% of projects predicted that they’d use crowdloans to raise funding, while 2 projects indicated that they will be bidding with their own funds. Either they changed their strategy or we can expect some individual bidders in the next sequence of auctions. Most projects said they would require at least a leasing period of 1 year, which is why all crowdloans were programmed to bid for the entirety of 8 leasing periods.

Descriptive statistics

In total there are 17 unique crowdloans that received funding during the campaign from 18892 unique accounts. A total number of 1,301,173 KSM was contributed to the crowdloan which equals to 325,293,234 USD (?? when price). This means, that in 12% of all available tokens are currently locked in crowdloans. In addition, 47% are currently staked. This leads to a staking rate of X percent with Y percent of KSM tokens locked in parachains.

Contribution dynamics

In the following graph, we illustrate the cumulative contributions to the available crowdloans. To make the graph more readable, we focus on the eight most funded crowdloans.

Slot 1-3

The winners for the first three slots were rather clear for quite a period of time. At the beginning, there was a close call between Shiden and Moonrive. Shiden started out with a lead but was quickly surpassed by Moonriver, which could sustain their position. The following graph illustrates the crowdloan contribution dynamic for the first three auctions. As bids correspond to the crowdloan contributions and there was no change in leading position during the termination phase of either of the first three auctions, this graph also illustrates the winners of the first 3 auctions.

Slot 4

The race for slot 4 was quite a lot more interesting and for quite a time it was not clear, which project could secure the 4th ever (openly auctioned off) Parachain Slot on Kusama. The teams of Bifrost and Khala were head to head with switching winners periodically. The following graph illustrates the race. However, there Khala secured the lead in all blocks within the ending period and therefore was destined to win the slot 4.

Only shortly before the ending period started, Khala was able to receive a big investment that secured their position and the leader of 100% of blocks within the ending period. Therefore, Khala could secure slot 4 on Kusama.

Slot 5

The fifth slot was a close race between Basilisk and Bifrost, with Basilisk catching up from behind. As can be seen in the next graph, Basilisk did only register their crowdloan at XX, which was quite suprising. They caught up to Bifrost quite fast and tried to overcome them. More than slot 4!

Let us increase the resolution and look at the block level.

We can see that during the ending phase, the leading position was frequently changed. However, Bifrost could sustain the lead most of time and it is therefore highly probable that they will win the slot. Specifically, Bifrost was leading 96.6% of the blocks during the ending phase.

Future prospects

We are living in exciting times where crowdloans finally arrived to the Kusama (and soon) Polkadot network. With the inclusion of Parachains, a blockchain that scales becomes more closer. This marks a milestone in the development of the protocol and pushes us into the next level. The first five projects that are live on Kusama are Karura, Moonriver, Shiden, Khala and X. (Link to platforms). As we saw in the analysis, all projects funded themselves with crowdloans. With those devices, the incentives are a bit different for the team than we’d assume for bidders in an auction. The general assumption in auctions is that bidders want the good as cheap as possible. However, this might be different in the situation with crowdloans, because the projects do not (at least mostly) fund the slot by themselves. Even contrary to traditional auctions, the projects might even benefit from their higher bids, because it signals a higher value to the market and might increase the token price. Additionally, crowdloan contributors face trade-offs when contributing to projects. First, they are not doing so solely based on their preferences, because contributing to your favorite project which is predicted not to win, would waste opportuninty costs (both of unbonding time, and the time the tokens are locked in crowdloans). Additionally, they might want to get in the project as early as possible. At some point, one could expect that the token price gets diluted if more funds go into a project, but this depends on how the parachain teams structure the rewards. If they mint more tokens to satisfy the increased demand in crowdloans, the token price should fall with higher supply. If, however, the token pool to be distributed is fixed and left over tokens remain in circulation, price should rather increase with more contributors (as network effect increases and the project has more outreach).

Generally, we can expect that future auctions are much more dynamic. On the one hand, we might see projects that are in the “on-boarding” phase (like all of them were in those sequence of auctions) where the use of crowdloans is natural and of great benefit. However, after being active, projects might be in the “extension” phase where they need to win other slots to sustain their operation. In this case, crowdloans might not be the best tool. Also, they might not go all for the full period but try to “flick” together their timetable based on where they can score the cheapest slots. In a survey prior to the auctions, around 30% of participating projects suggested that they will switch to some private form of bidding (i.e., non-crowdloans) in the future. Public bidding might be also including smart-contracts where funds are gathered in the platform’s native token (maybe even from treasury). The former is similar to ICOs where project source funds from the crowd and offer platform benefits in exchange. However, this might change in the extension phase, where projects might utilize their own treasury or saving to extend the funds or fund with their own tokens. The reason being that it offers more flexibility (crowdloans are rather “dumb” and even overbid themselves and also it might get harder to provide platform rewards for new users. Additionally, with parachains, smart-contracts are possible and make it possible to source funds trustless while offering an interface for some more sophisticated bidding strategies. And it reduces the effort of conducting a crowdloan campaign. More flexible to jump into bidding for slots that are starting but might be cheaper. Overlapping explaining.
